<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<assessmentItem xmlns="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqti_v2p1"
                xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
                xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqti_v2p1 http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqti_v2p1.xsd"
                identifier="ExpressionsWithVariables" title="Expressions with Variables" adaptive="false"
                timeDependent="false">
    <responseDeclaration identifier="RESPONSE" cardinality="multiple" baseType="identifier">
        <correctResponse>
            <value>ChoiceB</value>
            <value>ChoiceC</value>
            <value>ChoiceE</value>
        </correctResponse>
        <mapping lowerBound="0" upperBound="3">
            <mapEntry mapKey="ChoiceB" mappedValue="1"/>
            <mapEntry mapKey="ChoiceC" mappedValue="1"/>
            <mapEntry mapKey="ChoiceE" mappedValue="1"/>
        </mapping>
    </responseDeclaration>
    <outcomeDeclaration identifier="SCORE" cardinality="single" baseType="float"/>
    <itemBody>
        <p>
            Recall that in arithmetic we have come across expressions like (2 x 10) + 3, 3 + (4 x 5) etc.
            These expressions are formed from numbers and basic operations like addition, subtraction, multiplication
            and division.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Expressions can be formed from variables too.</strong>
            For example the expression
            <m:math title="2n" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                    <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            is formed by multiplying the variable n by 2; the expression
            <m:math title="(x+10)" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mrow>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>10</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                    </m:mrow>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            is formed by adding 10 to the variable
            <m:math title="x" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                    <m:mrow>
                        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                    </m:mrow>
                </m:mstyle>
            </m:math>
            .
        </p>
        <blockquote>
            <p>
                Note that a number expression
                like (4 x 3) + 5 can be immediately
                evaluated as (4 x 3) + 5 = 12 + 5 = 17.
                But an expression like
                <m:math title="4x+5" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                    <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                        <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>5</m:mn>
                    </m:mstyle>
                </m:math>
                ,
                which contains the variable
                <m:math title="x" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                    <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:mstyle>
                </m:math>
                ,
                cannot be evaluated.
                Only if
                <m:math title="x" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                    <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:mstyle>
                </m:math>
                is given some value, an expression like
                <m:math title="4x+5" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                    <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                        <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>5</m:mn>
                    </m:mstyle>
                </m:math>
                can be evaluated. For example
                when
                <m:math title="x" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                    <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:mstyle>
                </m:math>
                = 3,
                <m:math title="4x+5" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                    <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                        <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>5</m:mn>
                    </m:mstyle>
                </m:math>
                =
                (4 x 3) + 5 = 17.

            </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
            <strong>Check your understanding</strong>
        </p>
        <div class="well">
            <choiceInteraction responseIdentifier="RESPONSE"
                               maxChoices="0">
                <prompt>
                    <p>Which of the following is a variable expression ?</p>
                </prompt>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceA">(4 x 2) + 5</simpleChoice>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceB">
                    <m:math title="10y" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                        <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                            <m:mn>10</m:mn>
                            <m:mi>y</m:mi>
                        </m:mstyle>
                    </m:math>
                </simpleChoice>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceC">
                    <m:math title="2t + 15" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                        <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                            <m:mi>t</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>15</m:mn>
                        </m:mstyle>
                    </m:math>
                </simpleChoice>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceD">(10 + 5) / 15</simpleChoice>
                <simpleChoice identifier="ChoiceE">
                    <m:math title="5x+6y" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
                        <m:mstyle fontfamily="serif" displaystyle="true">
                            <m:mn>5</m:mn>
                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>6</m:mn>
                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                        </m:mstyle>
                    </m:math>
                </simpleChoice>
            </choiceInteraction>
        </div>

    </itemBody>
    <responseProcessing
            template="http://www.imsglobal.org/question/qti_v2p1/rptemplates/map_response"/>
</assessmentItem>